Add Documentation Example

Add to:

docs/architecture/edge-semantic-layer.md

Section:

Example Edge Projection

Example:

{
  "event_id": "EVT-2026-00491",
  "edge_profile": [
    {
      "edge_id": "EDGE-STRUCT-001",
      "domain": "STRUCTURAL",
      "relation": "LIQUIDITY_IMBALANCE",
      "state": "EDGE_OBSERVED",
      "confidence": 0.78,
      "evidence_links": [
        "EV-992"
      ],
      "provenance": {
        "source": "SEC_FILING",
        "timestamp": "2026-07-13T16:00:00Z"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Important note:

The output is:

"A liquidity imbalance structure was observed."

It is not:

"This creates a trading opportunity."

That distinction belongs in the contract.

Add E7 — No Forward Inference

I agree this deserves explicit status.

E7 — Evidence Boundary Preservation

Failure:

EDGE_FORWARD_INFERENCE

Rule:

EDGE may classify relationships present in evidence but may not create new facts, causal claims, or evidence artifacts.

Allowed:

Evidence:
Low available float
+
Increased demand indicators

EDGE:
Liquidity imbalance observed

Not allowed:

EDGE:
Future price increase likely

Test:

test('E7: EDGE_FORWARD_INFERENCE - Cannot create unsupported facts', () => {
  const payload = {
    classification: "LIQUIDITY_IMBALANCE",
    derived_claims: [
      "future_price_increase"
    ]
  };

  expect(() => validateEdgePayload(payload))
    .toThrow("EDGE_FORWARD_INFERENCE");
});

This is an important addition because E6 controls certainty magnitude, while E7 controls semantic direction.

Ontology Relations

I would approve adding relations, but rename them.

Avoid:

ASYM_HIGH_VOLATILITY

because it begins describing an observed market outcome.

Prefer:

STRUCTURAL_RELATIONS

├── SUPPLY_CONSTRAINT
├── LIQUIDITY_IMBALANCE
├── OWNERSHIP_CONCENTRATION
├── CAPACITY_CONSTRAINT
├── TIMING_WINDOW
├── REGULATORY_GATE
├── INFORMATION_ASYMMETRY
├── NETWORK_DEPENDENCY
└── OPTION_CONVEXITY

Why?

Because these are mechanisms.

They can exist before an outcome appears.

Example:

Supply Constraint
        ↓
possible volatility expression

The first is KRYLO territory.

The second is interpretation.

Updated Invariant Set

The contract becomes:

E1 Evidence Required
E2 Provenance Required
E3 Execution Boundary
E4 Unknown Preservation
E5 Layer Direction
E6 Semantic Escalation Prevention
E7 Evidence Boundary Preservation

This is a stronger contract.

Approval Recommendation

With those three changes:

✅ approve KRYL-1041
✅ create child implementation WOs
✅ begin implementation planning
✅ defer v3.10.0 stamp until merge

The addition of E7 is especially valuable. It closes the gap between:

"don't be too confident" (E6)

and

"don't invent a fact that wasn't observed" (E7)

Those are different failure modes, and separating them is exactly the type of precision the doctrine requires.

